Not too much so.  They tend to serve two different functions in society, really.  Clerics will (usually) be found in more urbane, &quot;developed&quot; societies, where the immediate connection to the land is more removed from the general populace.  In essence, the clerics serve the faithful to a particular codified doctrine.<br>
<br>
Druids will serve groups with a more immediate, direct link to the land.  Reliance is more on tradition and lore than on sacred texts in this case, ritual is used to directly invoke the diety instead of prayer being used to ask for intervention.<br>
<br>
The power of the druid lies in the direct tie to nature (in essence, a zen state of recognition of the interconnectivity of all living things).  The druid uses ritual to channel the power of the diety that is infused in the natural world THROUGH himself.<br>
<br>
The cleric uses prayer and scared texts to open a channel of communication between the individual and the divine.  It's a more personal, but less intimate arrangement, if that makes sense.  Hence, the stereotype that clerics are uptight and stodgy (ahem, High Elves) and druids are more wild and charged with a sexual energy (WOO HOO!  Wood Elves!)<br>
<br>
Look at Qeynos.  The clerics and paladins serve the city folk.  But, as you go further out into the Plains of Karana, you start to see more and more of the druids' influence.<br>
<br>
If you can see a person getting dressed up in some ornate chain to listen to a sermon, they are likely serviced by a cleric.  If you see them cavorting naked in the rain with a deer skull on their head, hopped up on psychodelic mushrooms, likely they hang with the druids.<br>
<br>
Just my hasty generalization.  Now where's my deer skull and mushrooms?<br>
